<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="430" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,611,2036]" pageId="3" pageNumber="430">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,1117,1143]" pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species is very close to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[723,822,1118,1143]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Bibio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="430" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marci">
<emphasis box="[723,822,1118,1143]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="430">B. marci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but presents in both genders distinct morphological features which allow a safe identification. In males the posterior femur is more clavate, with narrow basal part longer, reaching slightly beyond middle of femur (
<figureCitation box="[778,854,1194,1220]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,270,1843,1867]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Bibio spp. 1–3. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov. 1. Male habitus (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 5 mm. 2. Female wing (paratype, Montimannu), scale bar: 5 mm. 3. Male hind leg (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 2 mm. 4. Male hind leg of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) (Italy, Aosta province, St. Vincent). Photos by G. Haldimann." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); hind tarsus inflated (
<figureCitation box="[1135,1214,1194,1220]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,270,1843,1867]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Bibio spp. 1–3. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov. 1. Male habitus (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 5 mm. 2. Female wing (paratype, Montimannu), scale bar: 5 mm. 3. Male hind leg (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 2 mm. 4. Male hind leg of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) (Italy, Aosta province, St. Vincent). Photos by G. Haldimann." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Figs 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1230,1247,1194,1220]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1394,1418]" captionTargetBox="[160,1432,194,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-232@5.[151,1436,194,1370]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. Males of Bibio spp. 5–8. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov., scale bars: 1 mm. 5. Anterior tibia in posterior view (holotype). 6. Hind basitarsus in anterior view (holotype). 7. Hypopygium in dorsal view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 8. Hypopygium in ventral view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 9. Hind basitarsus of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) in posterior view (Aosta prov., St. Vincent)." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">6</figureCitation>
), decreasing in thickness from 1 
<superScript attach="left" box="[345,356,1233,1247]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="430">st</superScript>
to 5 
<superScript attach="left" box="[407,419,1233,1247]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="430">th</superScript>
tarsomere, instead of simple, not inflated, parallel-sided, as in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1151,1250,1236,1261]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Bibio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="430" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marci">
<emphasis box="[1151,1250,1236,1261]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="430">B. marci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<figureCitation box="[1311,1392,1236,1262]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,270,1843,1867]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Bibio spp. 1–3. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov. 1. Male habitus (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 5 mm. 2. Female wing (paratype, Montimannu), scale bar: 5 mm. 3. Male hind leg (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 2 mm. 4. Male hind leg of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) (Italy, Aosta province, St. Vincent). Photos by G. Haldimann." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Figs. 4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1404,1421,1236,1262]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1394,1418]" captionTargetBox="[160,1432,194,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-232@5.[151,1436,194,1370]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. Males of Bibio spp. 5–8. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov., scale bars: 1 mm. 5. Anterior tibia in posterior view (holotype). 6. Hind basitarsus in anterior view (holotype). 7. Hypopygium in dorsal view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 8. Hypopygium in ventral view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 9. Hind basitarsus of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) in posterior view (Aosta prov., St. Vincent)." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">9</figureCitation>
). In the female, the wing membrane is lighter, more greyish-white than brownish, hind veins not contrasting, hyaline or nearly so (
<figureCitation box="[399,470,1314,1340]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,270,1843,1867]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Bibio spp. 1–3. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov. 1. Male habitus (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 5 mm. 2. Female wing (paratype, Montimannu), scale bar: 5 mm. 3. Male hind leg (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 2 mm. 4. Male hind leg of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) (Italy, Aosta province, St. Vincent). Photos by G. Haldimann." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="431" pageId="3" pageNumber="430" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,611,2036]" pageId="3" pageNumber="430">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,350,1352,1378]" pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Description.</emphasis>
Male. Body 
<quantity box="[504,615,1352,1378]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="430" unit="mm" value="9.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="8.0">8–10 mm</quantity>
long. Black, with long and dense black pilosity in general appearance (
<figureCitation box="[160,232,1391,1417]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,270,1843,1867]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Bibio spp. 1–3. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov. 1. Male habitus (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 5 mm. 2. Female wing (paratype, Montimannu), scale bar: 5 mm. 3. Male hind leg (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 2 mm. 4. Male hind leg of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) (Italy, Aosta province, St. Vincent). Photos by G. Haldimann." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), with tibiae and tarsi lighter, brownish. Head. Black, with long black wavy pilosity, especially on occiput, eyes with long stiff pilosity. Ocellar tubercle prominent. Antennae black, flagellum 7-segmented. Palpi black, practically as long as antennae. Thorax. Mesonotum black, finely shagreened, weakly shining, postpronotal streak obscurely rufous (more so in Corsican specimens). Black pilosity, long and nearly wavy on dorsum and pleurae. Wing (
<figureCitation box="[523,594,1546,1572]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,270,1843,1867]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Bibio spp. 1–3. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov. 1. Male habitus (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 5 mm. 2. Female wing (paratype, Montimannu), scale bar: 5 mm. 3. Male hind leg (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 2 mm. 4. Male hind leg of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) (Italy, Aosta province, St. Vincent). Photos by G. Haldimann." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Length, 6.5– 
<quantity box="[775,845,1546,1572]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="430" unit="mm" value="8.0">8 mm</quantity>
, dirty whitish, with costal and most of radial cell brownish, pterostigma slightly darker brown, anterior veins brown-black, posterior veins translucent. Basal part of Rs more than twice as long as R-M cross-vein. Halteres black, with black stem. Coxae and femora black, with long, somewhat wavy, black pilosity, less so on hind femur. Anterior and mid tibiae castaneousbrown, hind tibia darker, brownish black. Tibiae and tarsi with shorter dark pilosity. Tarsi castaneous-brown, becoming darker towards tip, the individual tarsomeres more or less darkened at apex. Hind femur (
<figureCitation box="[1354,1426,1739,1765]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,270,1843,1867]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Bibio spp. 1–3. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov. 1. Male habitus (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 5 mm. 2. Female wing (paratype, Montimannu), scale bar: 5 mm. 3. Male hind leg (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 2 mm. 4. Male hind leg of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) (Italy, Aosta province, St. Vincent). Photos by G. Haldimann." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) brownish black, clavate, widening at or shortly after middle. Fore tibia with strong posterior projection (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 5–9" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1394,1418]" captionTargetBox="[160,1432,194,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-232@5.[151,1436,194,1370]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. Males of Bibio spp. 5–8. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov., scale bars: 1 mm. 5. Anterior tibia in posterior view (holotype). 6. Hind basitarsus in anterior view (holotype). 7. Hypopygium in dorsal view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 8. Hypopygium in ventral view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 9. Hind basitarsus of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) in posterior view (Aosta prov., St. Vincent)." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Posterior tibia (
<figureCitation box="[370,440,1816,1842]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,270,1843,1867]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Bibio spp. 1–3. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov. 1. Male habitus (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 5 mm. 2. Female wing (paratype, Montimannu), scale bar: 5 mm. 3. Male hind leg (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 2 mm. 4. Male hind leg of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) (Italy, Aosta province, St. Vincent). Photos by G. Haldimann." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) widening towards apex, first hind tarsomere (
<figureCitation box="[986,1061,1816,1842]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,270,1843,1867]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Bibio spp. 1–3. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov. 1. Male habitus (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 5 mm. 2. Female wing (paratype, Montimannu), scale bar: 5 mm. 3. Male hind leg (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 2 mm. 4. Male hind leg of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) (Italy, Aosta province, St. Vincent). Photos by G. Haldimann." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Figs 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1074,1089,1816,1842]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1394,1418]" captionTargetBox="[160,1432,194,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-232@5.[151,1436,194,1370]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. Males of Bibio spp. 5–8. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov., scale bars: 1 mm. 5. Anterior tibia in posterior view (holotype). 6. Hind basitarsus in anterior view (holotype). 7. Hypopygium in dorsal view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 8. Hypopygium in ventral view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 9. Hind basitarsus of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) in posterior view (Aosta prov., St. Vincent)." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">6</figureCitation>
) inflated, shorter and broader than in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[238,338,1855,1880]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Bibio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="430" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marci">
<emphasis box="[238,338,1855,1880]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="430">B. marci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, second tarsomere narrower and shorter than first, but distinctly inflated, third also somewhat inflated. Abdomen black, with long, somewhat wavy black pilosity. Hypopygium (
<figureCitation box="[1167,1279,1894,1920]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1394,1418]" captionTargetBox="[160,1432,194,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-232@5.[151,1436,194,1370]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. Males of Bibio spp. 5–8. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov., scale bars: 1 mm. 5. Anterior tibia in posterior view (holotype). 6. Hind basitarsus in anterior view (holotype). 7. Hypopygium in dorsal view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 8. Hypopygium in ventral view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 9. Hind basitarsus of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) in posterior view (Aosta prov., St. Vincent)." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Figs 7–8</figureCitation>
). Epandrium basally fused with base of gonocoxites, with U-shaped posterior emargination hardly reaching its half length (
<figureCitation box="[159,233,1971,1997]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1394,1418]" captionTargetBox="[160,1432,194,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-232@5.[151,1436,194,1370]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. Males of Bibio spp. 5–8. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov., scale bars: 1 mm. 5. Anterior tibia in posterior view (holotype). 6. Hind basitarsus in anterior view (holotype). 7. Hypopygium in dorsal view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 8. Hypopygium in ventral view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 9. Hind basitarsus of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) in posterior view (Aosta prov., St. Vincent)." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
), gonostyles strongly curved (
<figureCitation box="[592,665,1971,1997]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1394,1418]" captionTargetBox="[160,1432,194,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-232@5.[151,1436,194,1370]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. Males of Bibio spp. 5–8. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov., scale bars: 1 mm. 5. Anterior tibia in posterior view (holotype). 6. Hind basitarsus in anterior view (holotype). 7. Hypopygium in dorsal view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 8. Hypopygium in ventral view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 9. Hind basitarsus of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) in posterior view (Aosta prov., St. Vincent)." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
), cercus flattened, apically broadly rounded and pilose, aedeagal complex elongate, narrowly shovel-shaped, posterior emargination of sternite 9 complex, shallow (
<figureCitation box="[1311,1382,2010,2036]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1394,1418]" captionTargetBox="[160,1432,194,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-232@5.[151,1436,194,1370]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. Males of Bibio spp. 5–8. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov., scale bars: 1 mm. 5. Anterior tibia in posterior view (holotype). 6. Hind basitarsus in anterior view (holotype). 7. Hypopygium in dorsal view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 8. Hypopygium in ventral view (paratype, Rio Cannisoni). 9. Hind basitarsus of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) in posterior view (Aosta prov., St. Vincent)." pageId="3" pageNumber="430">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,526]" pageId="4" pageNumber="431">
Female. 
<quantity box="[302,436,152,178]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="431" unit="mm" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10–12 mm</quantity>
. Black with black pilosity in general appearance. Head. Frons granulate and hairy between the eyes. Palpi black, practically as long as antennae. Thorax black with black pilosity, notum feably shining, finely shagreened as in male. Wing (
<figureCitation box="[708,785,229,255]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,270,1843,1867]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1436,583,1817]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Bibio spp. 1–3. Bibio sardocyrneus sp. nov. 1. Male habitus (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 5 mm. 2. Female wing (paratype, Montimannu), scale bar: 5 mm. 3. Male hind leg (paratype, Villacidro), scale bar: 2 mm. 4. Male hind leg of Bibio marci (Linnaeus) (Italy, Aosta province, St. Vincent). Photos by G. Haldimann." pageId="4" pageNumber="431">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). 
<quantity box="[809,914,229,255]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="431" unit="mm" value="8.5" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="8.0">8–9 mm</quantity>
. Costal cell and most of radial cell brown, pterostigma darker brown, strongly contrasting, rest of wing membrane greyish-white tinged, lighter than in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[151,256,306,331]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Bibio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="431" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marci">
<emphasis box="[151,256,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="431">B. marci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with posterior veins not contrasting. Legs black and black pilose. Abdomen black with black pilosity.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="431" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,526]" pageId="4" pageNumber="431">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,339,383,409]" pageId="4" pageNumber="431">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haenni" authorityYear="2009" box="[482,639,384,409]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Bibio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="431" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sardocyrneus">
<emphasis box="[482,639,384,409]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="431">sardocyrneus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the geographical distribution of the new species. It is a composed latinized adjective, contraction of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haenni" authorityYear="2009" box="[689,782,423,448]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Dilophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="431" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sardous">
<emphasis box="[689,782,423,448]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="431">sardous</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(from Sardinia) and 
<emphasis box="[1035,1127,423,448]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="431">cyrneus</emphasis>
(from 
<emphasis box="[1212,1298,423,448]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="431">Cyrnos</emphasis>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1314,1405,422,448]" name="France" pageId="4" pageNumber="431">Corsica</collectingCountry>
in Greek).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,526]" box="[198,781,499,526]" pageId="4" pageNumber="431">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,338,499,525]" pageId="4" pageNumber="431">Chorotype.</emphasis>
A probable Sardo-Corsican endemic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
